, Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gulby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably a shortened form of English <b>Gooldsbury</b>, a variant of   Goldsborough  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Goldsborough","meanings":["English: habitational name from either of two places in North Yorkshire called Goldsborough. One, near Knaresborough, is named from the Old English personal name <i>Godel</i> + Old English <i>burh</i> ‘fortified place’. The other, near Whitby, is named from the Old English personal name <i>Golda</i> + <i>burh</i>."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Gulby was born about 1375, in England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with William Gulby."},"et":{"about 1375–":"umbes 1375–Surnud","1370–1439":"1370–1439","1408–1493":"1408–1493","1375–Female":"1375–Surnud","1375":"1375","1493":"1493","1408":"1408","1370":"1370","about 1375":"umbes 1375","1439":"1439","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Spelhurst Church, Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England"},"fi":{"about 1375–":"noin 1375–Kuollut","1370–1439":"1370–1439","1408–1493":"1408–1493","1375–Female":"1375–Kuollut","1375":"1375","1493":"1493","1408":"1408","1370":"1370","about 1375":"noin 1375","1439":"1439","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Spelhurst Church, Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England"},"fr":{"about 1375–":"environ 1375–Décédée","1370–1439":"1370–1439","1408–1493":"1408–1493","1375–Female":"1375–Décédée","1375":"1375","1493":"1493","1408":"1408","1370":"1370","about 1375":"environ 1375","1439":"1439","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Spelhurst Church, Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England":"Tunbridge Wells, Kent, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Joan Gulby est née environ 1375, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec William Gulby."},"de":{"about 1375–":"um 1375–Verstorben","1370–1439":"1370–1439","1408–1493":"1408–1493","1375–Female":"1375–Verstorben","1375":"1375","1493":"1493","1408":"1408","1370":"1370","about 1375":"um 1375","1439":"1439","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Spelhurst Church, Tunbridge Wells, Kent, England"